00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:09.110
He's a former board member of
the National Press Foundation

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:10.410
and he mastered his craft

00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:13.130
as a hard-boiled newspaper
beat reporter in Memphis,

00:01:13.130 --> 00:01:15.260
Cincinnati and Pittsburgh.

00:01:15.260 --> 00:01:17.290
As the book's title
suggests, there's more here

00:01:17.290 --> 00:01:20.650
than the makings of a story
double play trio made immortal

00:01:20.650 --> 00:01:23.240
in 1910 through the
poetic musings

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:26.450
of New York newspaper
columnist Franklin Pierce Adams.

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:28.420
In addition to seeing what
made the threesome tick

00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:32.010
and the dynamics of the Cubs
early 20th Century dynasty,

00:01:32.010 --> 00:01:34.920
the book illumines for us the
City of Chicago in the years

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:37.020
after it grabbed the
world's attention as host

00:01:37.020 --> 00:01:39.190
of the World Columbian
Exposition.

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:41.800
This is a fascinating read
whether you are a baseball fan

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:44.360
who likes history on the
side or a history buff

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.380
who likes a large
helping of baseball.

00:01:46.380 --> 00:01:48.880
After the talk there will
be time for questions.

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:51.510
So ladies and gentlemen,
David Rapp.

